Explanation:

1. Convert the input string to an integer (num) using `Integer.parseInt(s)`.
2. Calculate the mask representing the k-th power of 2 using `1 << k`.
3. Iterate from num to 1, decrementing i by mask in each iteration.
4. Within the loop, count the number of set bits in i using a while loop and the bitwise right shift operator (`>>`).
5. Add the count to the result variable.
6. Return the result modulo 1000000007 (prime number 7) to ensure the result is within the desired range.

This solution has a time complexity of O(log(n)) due to the iterative approach and a space complexity of O(1) since we only use a single variable (result) and no additional data structures. The energy implications are low since the algorithm is efficient and requires minimal resources.

